# HW11.0 Broadcast Versus Caching In Spark

paragraphs.title: What is the difference between broadcasting and caching data in Spark?
paragraphs.text:
%md

A [broadcast variable](http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/programming-guide.html#broadcast-variables) ensures that all partitions receive a materialized value in memory without having to bundle this value in a closure, and this value is shared by all partitions on the same node. A [cached variable](http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/programming-guide.html#rdd-persistence) represents elements that have been materialized from an RDD on some partition, but the cache is subject to a least-recently-used (LRU) eviction policy.

result.msg: A broadcast variable ensures that all partitions receive a materialized value in memory without having to bundle this value in a closure, and this value is shared by all partitions on the same node. A cached variable represents elements that have been materialized from an RDD on some partition, but the cache is subject to a least-recently-used (LRU) eviction policy.

paragraphs.title: Give an example (in the context of machine learning) of each mechanism (at a high level).
paragraphs.text:
%md

One example in the context of machine learning would be the PageRank algorithm. In PageRank, you would want all partitions to recognize the total number of nodes in the graph and any mass associated with dangling nodes so that they can properly apply the teleportation factor. In this case, you would want to broadcast the node count and the dangling node mass to all partitions. At the same time, you would want to avoid re-materializing the web graph in every iteration. Since the entire web graph would not fit in memory, you would instead opt for each partition remembering as much as possible (usually the specific values it materialized), and so you would cache the data.

# HW11.1  Loss Functions

paragraphs.title: In The Context Of Binary Classification Problems, Does The Linear SVM Learning Algorithm Yield The Same Result As A L2 Penalized Logistic Regression Learning Algorithm?
paragraphs.text:
%md

So far, the two do not yield the same result, though it has been demonstrated that a logistic regression that has both an L1 and L2 penalty can be reduced to a linear SVM ([reference](https://www.aaai.org/ocs/index.php/AAAI/AAAI15/paper/view/9856)). Unless that changes (one is shown to reduce to the other), the two can be seen to be minimizing different concepts, where linear SVM is minimizing margin while logistic regression is minimizing log loss (more details below). Therefore, the two can end up with different boundary hyperplanes, and thus different models.

paragraphs.title: Separating Surfaces for Linear SVM vs. Logistic Regression
paragraphs.text:
%md

In binary classification (assuming the named classes A and B for convenience), a linear SVM and logistic regression both have a hyperplane as a decision surface. In linear SVM, the hyperplane represents the separation of class A from class B that maximizes the margin, or the distance of each point to the hyperplane. In logistic regression, the hyperplane represents a probability threshold where all items on one side of the hyperplane are in class A with less than 50% likelihood while all items on the other side of the hyperplane are in class A with 50% likelihood or more.

In logistic regression, the hyperplane represents a probability threshold where all items on one side of the hyperplane are in class A with less than 50% likelihood while all items on the other side of the hyperplane are in class A with 50% likelihood or more.

paragraphs.title: In the context of binary classification problems, does the linear SVM learning algorithm yield the same result as a perceptron learning algorithm?
paragraphs.text:
%md

If the two classes are linearly separable, the two may yield different models, because the perceptron learning algorithm does not attempt to minimize the margin; rather, it is finished as soon as it finds a weight vector corresponding to any of the hyperplanes that are able to separate the two classes. If the two classes are not linearly separable, then assuming that we are talking about a hard SVM, then neither converges, which is essentially the same result, though the two may diverge to entirely different weight vectors.

paragraphs.title: In the context of logistic regression describe and define three flavors of penalized loss functions. Are These All Supported In Spark MLLib (Include Online References To Support Your Answers)?
paragraphs.text:
%angular As noted in the Apache Spark documentation (reference), in the context of logistic regression, there are three flavors of penalized loss functions supported by Spark MLLib.
  • L1 penalty (lasso): The model is penalized by the L1 norm of the weight vector, $\lVert \mathbf{w} \rVert_1$ (reference)
  • L2 penalty (ridge): The model is penalized by the L2 norm of the weight vector, $\frac{1}{2} \lVert \mathbf{w} \rVert_2^2$ (reference)
  • L1 and L2 penalty (elastic net): The model is penalized by a linear combination of the L1 norm and the L2 norm of the weight vector, $\alpha \lVert \mathbf{w} \rVert _1 + (1-\alpha)\frac{1}{2} \lVert \mathbf{w} \rVert_2^2$ (reference)

paragraphs.title: Describe probabilistic interpretations of the L1 and L2 priors for penalized logistic regression (HINT: see synchronous slides for week 11 for details)
paragraphs.text:
%md

The intuition is described in a Cross Validated post ([reference](http://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/163388/l2-regularization-is-equivalent-to-gaussian-prior)), and it is made more obvious from the visualizations of the probability surfaces presented in lecture slides from Brown University ([reference](https://cs.brown.edu/courses/archive/2006-2007/cs195-5/lectures/lecture13.pdf)). When using L1 penalties, we recognize that the value that minimizes the L1 norm is the median, which is equivalent to the result for the MLE estimator for a Laplace distribution. When using L2 penalties, we recognize that the value that minimizes the L2 norm is the sample mean, which is equivalent to the result for the MLE estimator for a Gaussian distribution. Therefore, when we look at probabilistic interpretations of the L1 and L2 priors, they can be interpreted as a Laplacian prior and a Gaussian prior, respectively.

paragraphs.title: Generate 2 sets of linearly separable data with 100 data points each using the data generation code provided below. Call One The Training Set And The Other The Testing Set. Plot Each In Separate Plots.
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

# Provided data generation code

from numpy.random import rand

def generateData(n):
    """ 
    generates a 2D linearly separable dataset with n samples. 
    The third element of the sample is the label
    """
    xb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
    yb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
    xr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
    yr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
    inputs = []
    for i in range(len(xb)):
        inputs.append([xb[i],yb[i],1])
        inputs.append([xr[i],yr[i],-1])
    return inputs

# Create the training set and testing set

training_set = np.array(generateData(100))
testing_set = np.array(generateData(100))

# Plot the data sets

def plot_data_set(data_set):
    data_colors = ['#0099ff' if x == 1 else '#ff5050' for x in data_set[:, 2]]
    plt.scatter(data_set[:, 0], data_set[:, 1], color=data_colors, alpha=0.5)

fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(16, 6)

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.title('training set')
plot_data_set(training_set)

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.title('testing set')
plot_data_set(testing_set)

showMPL()

paragraphs.title: Modify this data generation code to generate non-linearly separable training and testing datasets (with approximately 10% of the data falling on the wrong side of the separating hyperplane. Plot The Resulting Datasets.
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

def generateNonSeparableData(n, flip_rate=0.1):
    # Generate separable data, and then flip each element at 10% chance

    separable_data = generateData(n)
    non_separable_data = [x[:-1] + [-x[-1] if flip <= flip_rate else x[-1]] for x, flip in zip(separable_data, rand(n))]
    return non_separable_data

# Create the training set and testing set

training_set = np.array(generateNonSeparableData(100))
testing_set = np.array(generateNonSeparableData(100))

# Plot the data sets

fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(16, 6)

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.title('training set')
plot_data_set(training_set)

paragraphs.title: Using MLLib  train up a LASSO logistic regression model with the training dataset.
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

import functools

from pyspark.mllib.regression import LabeledPoint
from pyspark.mllib.classification import LogisticRegressionModel, LogisticRegressionWithSGD

# Use the last element as the label, all other elements as the features

def getLabeledPoint(point):
    label = 1 if point[-1] == 1 else 0
    return LabeledPoint(label, point[:-1])

# Create an RDD for the training set and test sets

training_rdd = sc.parallelize(training_set).map(getLabeledPoint).cache()
testing_rdd = sc.parallelize(testing_set).map(getLabeledPoint).cache()

actual_labels_rdd = testing_rdd.map(lambda x: x.label).cache()
testing_features_rdd = testing_rdd.map(lambda x: x.features).cache()

# Define a function to iterate on top of the weights from a previous logistic regression

def mllib_logistic_regression(previous_weights=None):
    model = LogisticRegressionWithSGD.train(data = training_rdd, regType='l1', iterations=1, initialWeights=previous_weights)
    return model.weights

# Initialize the weights and the tracking of the iterations

previous_weights = [1.0, 1.0]

mllib_iterations = []
mllib_weights = []

# Run iterations

for i in range(100):
    next_weights = mllib_logistic_regression(previous_weights)

    mllib_iterations.append(i + 1)
    mllib_weights.append(next_weights)

    previous_weights = next_weights

paragraphs.title: Evaluate With The Testing Set.
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

# Plot the weights for an iteration

def plot_weights(iteration_id, model_weights, xlim, ylim, line_style, line_width):
    slope = model_weights[0] / (-1 * model_weights[1])

    x_values = sorted([xlim[0], xlim[1], ylim[0] / slope, ylim[1] / slope])
    y_values = [x * slope for x in x_values]
    zip_values = np.array([(x, y) for x, y in zip(x_values, y_values) if y >= ylim[0] and y <= ylim[1]])

    plot_label = str(iteration_id) + ' iterations'
    plt.plot(zip_values[:, 0], zip_values[:, 1], linestyle=line_style, linewidth=line_width, label=plot_label, alpha=0.5)

# Plot the weights for all iterations

def evaluate_model_progress(iterations, weights, plot_step):
    
    # Initialize our plot
    
    fig = plt.gcf()
    fig.set_size_inches(12, 6)
    
    plt.title('model decision boundary vs. testing set')
    plot_data_set(testing_set)
    
    axes = plt.gca()
    
    xlim = axes.get_xlim()
    ylim = axes.get_ylim()
    
    # Plot each iteration
    
    indices = np.arange(plot_step - 1, len(iterations), plot_step)
    
    if plot_step > 1:
        plot_weights(iterations[0], weights[0], xlim, ylim, '--', 1)

    for i in indices:
        if i > 0 and i != (len(iterations) - 1):
            plot_weights(iterations[i], weights[i], xlim, ylim, '--', 1)

    plot_weights(iterations[-1], weights[-1], xlim, ylim, '-', 4)
    
    # There are a lot of iterations, so add the legend outside the bounding box
    
    box = axes.get_position()
    axes.set_position([box.x0, box.y0, box.width * 0.8, box.height])

    plt.xlim(xlim[0], xlim[1])
    plt.ylim(ylim[0], ylim[1])
    
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
    
    showMPL()

evaluate_model_progress(mllib_iterations, mllib_weights, 10)

paragraphs.title: What Is a good number of iterations for training the logistic regression model? Justify with plots.
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

# Initialize our plot

fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(16, 6)

# Compute accuracy for the given set of weights using the testing set

def get_accuracy(model_weights):
    model = LogisticRegressionModel(model_weights, 0.0, 2, 2)

    # Compare the predictions with the actual result

    predicted_labels_rdd = model.predict(testing_features_rdd)

    return predicted_labels_rdd.zip(actual_labels_rdd).map(lambda x: 1.0 if x[0] == x[1] else 0.0).mean()

# Plot our accuracies

mllib_accuracies = [get_accuracy(model_weights) for model_weights in mllib_weights]
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.title('accuracy')
plt.plot(mllib_iterations, mllib_accuracies)

# Returns how much the model has changed

def get_model_changes(prev_weights, next_weights):
    weight_change = np.array(prev_weights) - np.array(next_weights)
    return np.linalg.norm(weight_change)

# Plot our model changes

mllib_model_changes = [get_model_changes(prev_weights, next_weights) for prev_weights, next_weights in zip(mllib_weights[:-1], mllib_weights[1:])]
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.title('model change')
plt.plot(mllib_iterations[1:], mllib_model_changes)

showMPL()

paragraphs.title: What Is A Good Number Of Iterations For Training The Logistic Regression Model? Justify With Words. (Part 1)
What Is A Good Number Of Iterations For Training The Logistic Regression Model? Justify With Words. (Part 2)
paragraphs.text:
%angular

Initial accuracy is strongly dependent on the starting weights. Starting with [0, 0] for example, the accuracy hits its max immediately, while starting with [1, 1] introduces a less optimal initial accuracy that then switches to the correct accuracy within 10 iterations. Therefore, from an accuracy perspective, we can stop after it hit 93% accuracy, which was the first itration for [0, 0] or the sixth iteration for [1, 1]. The model change drops to the 0.01 threshold at around 72 iterations. If we were to use the change in the model as our measure of what would be a good number of iterations, we would stop at 72 iterations. Since 100 essentially satisfies both of our concerns (a stable model and one that has good accuracy), we would use 100 iterations for training this logistic regression model.

paragraphs.title: Derive and implement in Spark a weighted  LASSO logistic regression. Weight each example using the inverse vector length (Euclidean norm).

paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

weighted_training_rdd = training_rdd.map(lambda x: (x, 1 / np.linalg.norm(x.features))).cache()

# Define a function to iterate on top of the weights from a previous logistic regression

def weighted_logistic_regression(previous_weights=None, learning_rate = 0.05, reg_param = 0.1):
    if previous_weights is None:
        previous_weights = [0.0, 0.0]

    # Broadcast the model weights

    model_weights = sc.broadcast(previous_weights)

    # Define the loss function here so that it has access to the broadcast variable

    def get_weighted_loss(x):
        point, point_weight = x

        label = point.label if point.label == 1.0 else -1.0
        features = point.features
    
        # Compute the label-normalized features and dot product
    
        label_normalized_features = label * np.array(features)
    
        dot_product = np.dot(model_weights.value, features)
        label_normalized_dot_product = -label * dot_product
    
        # Compute the base loss
    
        base_loss = (1 / (1 + np.exp(label_normalized_dot_product)) - 1) * label_normalized_features
        
        # Apply weight
        
        weighted_loss = base_loss * point_weight
        
        return weighted_loss, point_weight

    # Compute the new gradient

    gradient = weighted_training_rdd.map(get_weighted_loss).reduce(lambda x, y: (x[0] + y[0], x[1] + y[1]))

    # Apply regularization penalty

    l1_penalty = reg_param * np.sign(model_weights.value)

    # Apply the gradient

    next_weights = previous_weights + l1_penalty - learning_rate * gradient[0] / gradient[1]

    return next_weights

%spark.pyspark

# Initialize the weights and the tracking of the iterations

previous_weights = [0.0, 0.0]

normed_iterations = []
normed_weights = []

converged = False

# Run iterations until we have converged. We'll assume convergence is when the change
# in the model is below 0.01. We'll also add a safety net of 100 iterations in case the
# model cannot converge.

iteration_id = 0

while not converged and iteration_id < 100:
    iteration_id += 1
    next_weights = weighted_logistic_regression(previous_weights)

    normed_iterations.append(iteration_id)
    normed_weights.append(next_weights)
    
    model_change = get_model_changes(previous_weights, next_weights)

    if iteration_id > 1:
        converged = model_change <= 0.01

    previous_weights = next_weights

if converged:
    print 'Converged in', len(normed_iterations), 'iterations'
else:
    print 'Failed to converge in', len(normed_iterations), 'iterations'

from pyspark.mllib.classification import SVMModel, SVMWithSGD

# Define a function to iterate on top of the weights from a previous SVM

def mllib_svm(previous_weights):
    model = SVMWithSGD.train(data = training_rdd, regType='l2', iterations=1, initialWeights=previous_weights)
    return model.weights

# Initialize the weights and the tracking of the iterations

previous_weights = [1.0, 1.0]

mllib_svm_iterations = []
mllib_svm_weights = []

# Run iterations

for i in range(100):
    next_weights = mllib_svm(previous_weights)

    mllib_svm_iterations.append(i + 1)
    mllib_svm_weights.append(next_weights)

    previous_weights = next_weights
    
evaluate_model_progress(mllib_svm_iterations, mllib_svm_weights, 10)

%spark.pyspark

# Define a function to iterate on top of the weights from a previous SVM iteration

def weighted_svm(previous_weights=None, learning_rate = 0.05, reg_param = 0.1):
    if previous_weights is None:
        previous_weights = [0.0, 0.0]

    # Broadcast the model weights

    model_weights = sc.broadcast(previous_weights)

    # Define filter function for support vectors here so that it has access to the broadcast variable

    def is_support_vector(x):
        point = x[0]

        label = point.label if point.label == 1.0 else -1.0
        features = point.features

        dot_product = np.dot(model_weights.value, features)
        label_normalized_dot_product = label * dot_product

        return label_normalized_dot_product < 1

    # Define the loss function here so that it has access to the broadcast variable

    def get_weighted_loss(x):
    	point, point_weight = x

        label = point.label if point.label == 1.0 else -1.0
        features = point.features

        label_normalized_features = label * np.array(features)

        # Base loss is the label-normalized features
    
        base_loss = label_normalized_features
        
        # Apply weight
        
        weighted_loss = base_loss * point_weight
        
        return weighted_loss, point_weight

    # Compute the new gradient

    support_vectors_rdd = weighted_training_rdd.filter(is_support_vector)
    gradient = support_vectors_rdd.map(get_weighted_loss).reduce(lambda x, y: (x[0] + y[0], x[1] + y[1]))

    # Apply regularization penalty

    l2_penalty = np.array([0.0, 0.0])

    # Apply the gradient

    next_weights = previous_weights + l2_penalty + learning_rate * gradient[0] / gradient[1]

    return next_weights
